Q9. (Theory) Explain the difference between git pull, git fetch, and git clone. When would you use each?
git pull- 
does a fetch and immediately merges (or rebases) those changes into your current branch. Use it when you're ready to actually bring remote changes into your working branch right now.
git fetch-
downloads new commits, branches, and tags from the remote, but doesn't touch your working files or current branch. It just updates your local view of the remote (e.g. origin/main). Use it when you want to see what's changed remotely before deciding what to do, a safe way to check in.
git clone-
copies an entire remote repository to your machine for the first time, including all branches, history and tags. Sets up the remote ("origin") automatically. Use it once, when starting work on a repo you don't have locally yet.

Q10. (Theory) What is a .gitignore file? Write a .gitignore for an Arduino project that excludes compiled output files (.hex, .elf), OS-specific files (.DS_Store, Thumbs.db), and IDE config folders (.vscode/, build/).
A .gitignore file tells Git which files and folders should not be tracked or uploaded to the repository. It is used to ignore temporary files, compiled files, build outputs and IDE configuration files.
Example .gitignore for an Arduino Project:
# Compiled output files
*.hex
*.elf
# OS-specific files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
# IDE configuration folders
.vscode/
build/
